&lt;figure>
&lt;img class="my-0 rounded-md" loading="lazy" src="https://dasarpai.github.io/assets/images/wiapost/5292-meaning-of-ahamkar-in-bhagavad-gita.jpg" alt="The Meaning of Ahamkar in Bhagwat Gita" />
&lt;/figure>
&lt;/p>
&lt;h1 class="relative group">The Meaning of Ego in Bhagwat Gita
&lt;div id="the-meaning-of-ego-in-bhagwat-gita" class="anchor">&lt;/div>
&lt;span
class="absolute top-0 w-6 transition-opacity opacity-0 ltr:-left-6 rtl:-right-6 not-prose group-hover:opacity-100">
&lt;a class="group-hover:text-primary-300 dark:group-hover:text-neutral-700"
style="text-decoration-line: none !important;" href="#the-meaning-of-ego-in-bhagwat-gita" aria-label="Anchor">#&lt;/a>
&lt;/span>
&lt;/h1>
&lt;h2 class="relative group">Ahamkaara vs Ego
&lt;div id="ahamkaara-vs-ego" class="anchor">&lt;/div>
&lt;span
class="absolute top-0 w-6 transition-opacity opacity-0 ltr:-left-6 rtl:-right-6 not-prose group-hover:opacity-100">
&lt;a class="group-hover:text-primary-300 dark:group-hover:text-neutral-700"
style="text-decoration-line: none !important;" href="#ahamkaara-vs-ego" aria-label="Anchor">#&lt;/a>
&lt;/span>
&lt;/h2>
&lt;p>In my view, the distinction between &lt;strong>Ahamkaara&lt;/strong> and &lt;strong>Ego&lt;/strong> is subtle yet profound, especially when viewed from a philosophical and spiritual lens. Ahamkara is &lt;strong>a tool that can be refined&lt;/strong>, whereas ego is &lt;strong>an illusion that must be dissolved&lt;/strong>. If Ahamkara leads to the realization that &lt;strong>all is one&lt;/strong>, it becomes a stepping stone to enlightenment. But if it binds one to the material world, it becomes just another name for ego.&lt;/p></description></item><item><title>How to Overcome the Ego and Find Joy in Life?</title><link>https://dasarpai.github.io/wiaposts/overcome-ego-and-find-joy-in-life/</link><pubDate>Sun, 16 Mar 2025 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><author>hari@dasarpai.com (Dr. Hari Thapliyaal)</author><guid>https://dasarpai.github.io/wiaposts/overcome-ego-and-find-joy-in-life/</guid><description>&lt;p>
&lt;figure>
&lt;img class="my-0 rounded-md" loading="lazy" src="https://dasarpai.github.io/assets/images/wiapost/5290-overcome-ego-and-find-joy-in-life.jpg" alt="Ego and Joy of Life" />
&lt;/figure>
&lt;/p>
&lt;h1 class="relative group">Ego and Joy of Life
&lt;div id="ego-and-joy-of-life" class="anchor">&lt;/div>
&lt;span
class="absolute top-0 w-6 transition-opacity opacity-0 ltr:-left-6 rtl:-right-6 not-prose group-hover:opacity-100">
&lt;a class="group-hover:text-primary-300 dark:group-hover:text-neutral-700"
style="text-decoration-line: none !important;" href="#ego-and-joy-of-life" aria-label="Anchor">#&lt;/a>
&lt;/span>
&lt;/h1>
&lt;p>If you think, &lt;em>&amp;ldquo;The ego within us &lt;br>
wants to do something difficult because, &lt;br>
against the difficult, one feels, &lt;br>
&amp;lsquo;I am someone, doing such a difficult thing,&amp;rsquo;&amp;rdquo;&lt;/em> &lt;br>
then think again.&lt;/p>
&lt;p>It is not about seeking difficulty. &lt;br>
If you challenge someone by asking, &lt;br>
&lt;em>&amp;ldquo;Why are you doing X in the most difficult way?&amp;rdquo;&lt;/em> &lt;br>
they will likely respond, &lt;br>
&lt;em>&amp;ldquo;This is the easiest and simplest way.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/em>&lt;/p></description></item><item><title>Is Ego Bad?</title><link>https://dasarpai.github.io/wiaposts/is-ego-bad/</link><pubDate>Sun, 15 Dec 2024 08:33:00 +0530</pubDate><author>hari@dasarpai.com (Dr. Hari Thapliyaal)</author><guid>https://dasarpai.github.io/wiaposts/is-ego-bad/</guid><description>&lt;p>
&lt;figure>
&lt;img class="my-0 rounded-md" loading="lazy" src="https://dasarpai.github.io/assets/images/wiapost/5274-Is-Ego-Bad.jpg" alt="Is Ego Bad?" />
&lt;/figure>
&lt;/p>
&lt;h1 class="relative group">Is Ahamkar Bad?
&lt;div id="is-ahamkar-bad" class="anchor">&lt;/div>
&lt;span
class="absolute top-0 w-6 transition-opacity opacity-0 ltr:-left-6 rtl:-right-6 not-prose group-hover:opacity-100">
&lt;a class="group-hover:text-primary-300 dark:group-hover:text-neutral-700"
style="text-decoration-line: none !important;" href="#is-ahamkar-bad" aria-label="Anchor">#&lt;/a>
&lt;/span>
&lt;/h1>
&lt;p>First, we need to understand.&lt;br>
The Sanskrit word &amp;ldquo;Ahamkara&amp;rdquo;&lt;br>
is not the same as &amp;ldquo;ego.&amp;rdquo;&lt;br>
Similarly, the Hindi word &amp;ldquo;Ghamand&amp;rdquo;&lt;br>
is not the same as &amp;ldquo;proud.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p>
&lt;p>Those who know Hindi understand,&lt;br>
&amp;ldquo;Ghamand&amp;rdquo; is bad, but pride is good.&lt;br>
Similarly, having Ahamkara is fine.&lt;br>
But having an ego is the problem.&lt;/p></description></item></channel></rss>